I"ù<p>During residency, it is economically advantageous to maximize your investment in a Roth IRA versus reducing your interest burden by paying off an equivalent amount of medical school debt. How much better? For each dollar you shift to a Roth IRA, you could be eight dollars better off in the long run. Contribute $15,000 while your income is low and it could be worth $120,000 or more when you retire. Here I will explain why the Roth IRA is a good financial decision for young doctors-in-training.</p>
